arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGreen growth has proven to be politically popular, but economically elusive. Can Green Sustain Growth? asks how we can move from theoretical support to implementation, and argues that this leap will require radical experimentation. But systemic change is costly, and a sweeping shift cannot be accomplished without political support, not to mention large-scale cooperation between business and government. Insightful and timely, this book brings together eight original, international case studies to consider what we can learn from the implementation of green growth strategies to date. This analysis reveals that coalitions for green experimentation emerge and survive when they link climate solutions to specific problems with near-term benefits that appeal to both environmental and industrial interests. Based on these findings, the volume delivers concrete policy recommendations for the next steps in the necessary shift toward sustainable prosperity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aClean energy industriesxGovernment policyvCase studies. 0aEnergy developmentxEnvironmental aspectsxGovernment policyvCase studies. 0aEnergy policyxEnvironmental aspectsvCase studies. 0aSustainable developmentxGovernment policyvCase studies. 4aGreen growth. 4aclimate change. 4aeconomic growth. 4aemissions reduction. 4aenergy system. 4ainnovation. 4apolitical economy. 4atechnological change. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh1 aHuberty, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788571zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de G